Introduction to Mixed Models using R

Dominique Makowski

May 2021

What are Mixed Models

All statistical tests are linear models

https://lindeloev.github.io/tests-as-linear (Google “tests linear models”)

Whole World of Models

  • LM: Linear Model
  • GLM: General Linear Model (logistic, count, zero-inflated, …)
  • GAM: General Additive Model
  • GLMM / GAMM: Mixed GLM / GAM
  • Bayesian Models
  • e.g. Bayesian Mixed Zero-Inflated General Additive Model

What does “Mixed” Mean

  • Full name actually “Mixed Effects” Model
  • Includes random effects on top of the fixed effects (the model’s main predictors)
  • Confusing names
  • Better term is “Hierarchical” Model
  • Hierarchical data is organized in groups which by themselves explain some variance
  • Groups can be any structure in the data, e.g., participants, items, datasets, …

Why use Mixed Models

  • Powerful (allows the quantification of a lot of interesting parameters)
  • Appropriate for the data we have in psychology / neuroscience
  • In 99% of cases, there is no reason to use anything else than mixed models
  • Should be the default of stats in psychology

Data

# Load data from URL (must be on one line)
df <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/
                DominiqueMakowski/teaching/master/
                R/2021_05_CBL_MixedModels/data.csv")
report(df)
## The data contains 1000 observations of the following 3 variables:
##   - RT: n = 1000, Mean = 6.21, SD = 4.30, Median = 5.99, MAD = 4.67, range: [-6.62, 18.17], Skewness = 0.04, Kurtosis = -0.41, 0% missing
##   - Difficulty: n = 1000, Mean = -6.15, SD = 3.60, Median = -6.09, MAD = 4.46, range: [-14.53, 1.75], Skewness = 9.05e-04, Kurtosis = -1.02, 0% missing
##   - Participant: 40 entries, such as S01 (2.50%); S02 (2.50%); S03 (2.50%) and 37 others (0 missing)

Aim

  • 25 participants did a task with 30 trials
  • For each trial, their RT was recorded and they reported the “subjective” difficulty
  • What’s the relationship between RT and Subjective Difficulty?
  • Hypothesis: Higher subjective difficulty = Higher RT (slower reaction)

ANOVA

Summarize the data by participant (aka, get individual difficulty scores)

  • repeated-measures ANOVAs are a statistical abominations
  • We need to group participants based on their average RT and reported difficulty
dfsub <- df %>% 
  group_by(Participant) %>% 
  summarise_all(mean)

dfsub

Dichotomize the participants

  • We split the participants into 2 groups based on their average difficulty
dfsub$Difficulty_Group <- ifelse(dfsub$Difficulty < mean(dfsub$Difficulty),
                                 "Reported_Easy", "Reported_Hard")

Run an ANOVA

model <- aov(RT ~ Difficulty_Group, data = dfsub)

report(model)
## For one-way between subjects designs, partial eta squared is equivalent to eta squared.
## Returning eta squared.
## The ANOVA (formula: RT ~ Difficulty_Group) suggests that:
## 
##   - The main effect of Difficulty_Group is statistically significant and large (F(1, 38) = 104.09, p < .001; Eta2 = 0.73, 90% CI [0.61, 0.81])
## 
## Effect sizes were labelled following Field's (2013) recommendations.

Conclusion

  • :shrug:

Conclusion (2)

  • ANOVAs are just uninformative summaries of linear models
model <- anova(lm(RT ~ 1 + Difficulty_Group, data = dfsub))

report(model)
## For one-way between subjects designs, partial eta squared is equivalent to eta squared.
## Returning eta squared.
## The ANOVA suggests that:
## 
##   - The main effect of Difficulty_Group is statistically significant and large (F(1, 38) = 104.09, p < .001; Eta2 = 0.73, 90% CI [0.61, 0.81])
## 
## Effect sizes were labelled following Field's (2013) recommendations.

Linear Model

  • \(y = a + b_{x}\) equivalent to \(y \thicksim a_{1} + b_{x}\)
  • becomes in R: \(response \thicksim Intercept(1) + \beta 1(Var1)\)

In R

  • The “Intercept” (~ 1 + ...) is added by default
model <- lm(RT ~ Difficulty_Group, data = dfsub)

report(model)
## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict RT with Difficulty_Group (formula: RT ~ Difficulty_Group). The model explains a statistically significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2 = 0.73, F(1, 38) = 104.09, p < .001, adj. R2 = 0.73). The model's intercept, corresponding to Difficulty_Group = Reported_Easy, is at 9.10 (95% CI [8.29, 9.91], t(38) = 22.72, p < .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of Difficulty_Group [Reported_Hard] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -5.78, 95% CI [-6.92, -4.63], t(38) = -10.20, p < .001; Std. beta = -1.69, 95% CI [-2.03, -1.35])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset.

Linear Mixed Model

Using all data

model <- lm(RT ~ Difficulty, data = df)

summary(report(model))
## We fitted a linear model to predict RT with Difficulty. The model's explanatory power is substantial (R2 = 0.51, adj. R2 = 0.51). The model's intercept is at 0.97 (95% CI [0.60, 1.34]). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of Difficulty is statistically significant and negative (beta = -0.85, 95% CI [-0.90, -0.80], t(998) = -32.16, p < .001, Std. beta = -0.71)

Problems:

  • Assumed independence of observations
  • Inflated statistical power
  • Information about group lost

Solutions:

  • Mixed model

Mixed model (random intercept)

model <- lmer(RT ~ Difficulty + (1|Participant), data = df)

report(model)
## We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict RT with Difficulty (formula: RT ~ Difficulty). The model included Participant as random effect (formula: ~1 | Participant). The model's total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.77) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.05. The model's intercept, corresponding to Difficulty = 0, is at 8.40 (95% CI [6.67, 10.14], t(996) = 9.49, p < .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of Difficulty is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.36, 95% CI [0.20, 0.51], t(996) = 4.48, p < .001; Std. beta = 0.30, 95% CI [0.17, 0.43])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using the Wald approximation.

Get parameters

parameters(model, effects = "fixed")
## # Fixed Effects
## 
## Parameter   | Coefficient |   SE |        95% CI | t(996) |      p
## ------------------------------------------------------------------
## (Intercept) |        8.40 | 0.89 | [6.67, 10.14] |   9.49 | < .001
## Difficulty  |        0.36 | 0.08 | [0.20,  0.51] |   4.48 | < .001

Visualizing - random

viz_data_random <- estimate_relation(model, 
                                     include_random = TRUE, 
                                     preserve_range = TRUE,
                                     length = 100)

p <- p + 
  geom_line(data = viz_data_random, aes(color = Participant))
p

  • The model estimates two “fixed” parameters (accross participants) of difficulty: the intercept and the slope
  • It estimates intercepts for all groups (the “random” variable)
  • The “fixed” effects are informed by random effects, and vice versa (shrinkage)

Mixed model (random intercept and random slope)

model <- lmer(RT ~ 1 + Difficulty + (1 + Difficulty | Participant), data = df)

parameters(model, effects = "fixed")
## # Fixed Effects
## 
## Parameter   | Coefficient |   SE |       95% CI | t(994) |      p
## -----------------------------------------------------------------
## (Intercept) |        8.20 | 0.83 | [6.57, 9.84] |   9.84 | < .001
## Difficulty  |        0.36 | 0.08 | [0.20, 0.51] |   4.44 | < .001
  • Both the intercept and the slope are estimated as fixed effects and for each level of the random variable

Visualizing

p <- ggplot(data = viz_data, aes(x = Difficulty, y = Predicted)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = CI_low, ymax = CI_high), alpha = 0.3) + 
  geom_point(data = df, aes(x = Difficulty, y = RT, color = Participant))

Back to the individual scores

dfsub$random_coef <- dfrandom %>% 
  filter(Parameter == "(Intercept)") %>% 
  pull(Coefficient)

report(cor.test(dfsub$Difficulty, dfsub$random_coef))
## Effect sizes were labelled following Funder's (2019) recommendations.
## 
## The Pearson's product-moment correlation between dfsub$Difficulty and dfsub$random_coef is negative, statistically significant, and very large (r = -1.00, 95% CI [-1.00, -0.99], t(38) = -63.55, p < .001)
